{
  "answer": "**Yājñavalkya Smṛti 2.21** does not directly address witnesses.[^1] It instead sets a rule for resolving conflicts between Smṛtis (traditional legal texts): reason grounded in custom prevails in legal (*vyavahāra*) matters, though Dharmaśāstra texts take precedence over Arthaśāstra.[^1]\n\nWitnesses (*sākṣin*) are one of three primary proofs (alongside documents and possession), with ordeals prescribed if none are available; they are detailed starting in verse 2.68 under \"5. Witnesses\" (*sākṣiprakaraṇam*):[^2]\n\n- **Qualified witnesses** (2.68–69): At least three, such as ascetics, the charitable, those of good family, truth-tellers, the dharmic, upright men, fathers, and the wealthy. They should be devoted to Vedic rites, ideally matching the parties' *varṇa* and caste (though any may suffice).[^3]\n- **Incompetent witnesses** (2.70–71): Women, children, the elderly, gamblers, drunkards, the insane, those accused of grave sins, actors, heretics, forgers, the sensorially impaired; also outcastes, friends, those with financial stakes, associates, enemies, thieves, violent persons, convicts, and exiles.[^4]\n- **Exceptions and admonition** (2.72–75): A single dharmic witness approved by both parties suffices; anyone may witness adultery, theft, assault, or violence. Judges admonish witnesses of dire karmic consequences for false testimony.[^5]\n- **Non-testimony and conflicts** (2.76–80): Withholding testimony on a debt incurs full repayment plus a fine after 46 days; equals false testimony in sin. Majority rules; if equal, the more virtuous prevail; superior or double-numbered later witnesses override earlier ones.[^6]\n- **Punishments** (2.81–83): False witnesses pay double the dispute's value (Brāhmaṇas banished); recanting testimony incurs an eightfold fine (Brāhmaṇas banished). False testimony is permitted (with purification) if true testimony would cause certain death to any *varṇa*.[^7]\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-048b9a).\n\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-e6e133).\n\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-5c0bb3) (includes p-5c0bb3 through p-18320c).\n\n[^4]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-478abd) (includes p-478abd through p-f5049f).\n\n[^5]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-33a082) (includes p-33a082 through p-2034fe).\n\n[^6]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-16fa67) (includes p-16fa67 through p-fbf5a7).\n\n[^7]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 2, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-dbd716) (includes p-dbd716 through p-5cd0fa).",
